  "prompt": "Has any Modi supporter turned into a Kejriwal supporter?",
  "response": "Political affiliations and support can change over time, influenced by various factors such as policy decisions, leadership styles, personal experiences, and public sentiment. Individual cases of people shifting their support from Narendra Modi to Arvind Kejriwal (or vice versa) could certainly exist, although comprehensive data or statistics specifically documenting such shifts may not be readily accessible.\n\nSupporters of political figures might change their allegiance due to:\n\n1. **Policy Changes**: Disagreement with key policies or decisions made by one leader may drive supporters to seek alternatives who better align with their views.\n2. **Performance Evaluation**: Perceived effectiveness in governance and delivery of promises can influence support. \n3. **Personal Experiences**: Direct impact of policies or administrative changes on personal life can trigger a shift in support.\n4. **Leadership Qualities**: Changes in perception regarding the leadership qualities, integrity, and vision of a political figure can impact support.\n5. **Political Developments**: Emergence of new information, scandals, successes, or failures can prompt reevaluation of support.\n\nFor instance, supporters who believed in Modi's vision for economic reforms or nationalistic initiatives might shift their support to Kejriwal if they feel his governance style at the state level has better addressed pressing issues like education, healthcare, or corruption.\n\nUltimately, shifts in political support are part of the dynamic nature of democratic societies, reflecting the evolving priorities and beliefs of individuals.",
